support.material:
Paper quires with the inner- and outermost leaves of parchment; the paper is folded in folio. Folios 2-91: Lettre G ( 55 35 ) in the centre of the folio, comparable to Briquet 9193, which is located to Italy and dated to 1379.
Folios 94-107: Demi-licorne ( 60 35 ) in the centre of the folio, comparable to Briquet 9929, which is located to Italy and dated to 1383/1393.
Folios 108-[b]: Monts ( 90 35 ) in the centre of the folio, comparable to Briquet 11853, which is located to Italy and dated to 1378/1390.

extent.seg:
i + 173 leaves.
The first endleaf at the beginning has been pasted on the inside of the upper cover and the last leaf has been pasted on the inside of the lower cover.

foliation.note: Numbering in Arabic numerals in brown ink in the upper right-hand corner of the rectos, but mostly cropped due to retrimming of the leaves.
Numbering in pencil in the upper right-hand corner of the rectos.

collation.p:
The manuscript comprises quires of various sizes, mainly 16 but also 14 and 12 leaves, and one of six leaves. The final quire has been heavily repaired, however the occurrence of the watermarks makes it possible to determine its structure. Both the first and second leaves (ff. 165-166) show watermarks and therefore cannot originally have been conjoint with the rear pastedown, where a watermark is also visible. The third leaf (f. 167), however, does not contain a watermark, and so must be the counterpart to the rear pastedown. The conclusion of the text on f. 173v with a scribal colophon (and the absence of any evidence to indicate the loss of other textual contents) points therefore to the 11th and 12th leaves having been cancelled, rather than lost.
Quires 1-216 (ff. 1-32)
Quires 3-414 (ff. 33-60)
Quires 5-716 (ff. 61-108)
Quire 814 (ff. 109-122)
Quire 96 (ff. 123r-128v)
Quires 10-1212 (ff. 129-164)
Quire 1312-2 (ff. 165-173: 11th-12th leaves cancelled, 10th is the rear pastedown)

signatures.p: Quire numbers in brown ink the lower margins of the first rectos of quires 4, 5, 7; and the number 3 in red ink on the first recto of quire 10

catchwords.seg: Catchwords written in brown ink and underlined with red ink in the lower right-hand corners of the last versos of quires

supportDesc.condition: Folio 48 has been largely torn out. There are large (? ink) stains on ff. 70r-71r. There is some water damage to the outer margins of leaves at the end. The outer margins of the leaves from f. 165 onwards are very frail.

layout.seg: Folios 1r-108r ruled in ink, frame only. Two columns, 45-46 lines to the page, written below top line.
Folios 109r-173v ruled in plummet, frame only. Two columns, 45-46 lines to the page written below top line.

handNote.p: Copied by a single scribe in Gothica Cursiva Libraria [according to Thomson (2016), an Anglicana-Secretary script]; the scribe signs his name as 'Scaep' or 'P. Scaep' throughout the manuscript: ff. 108r, 124r, 132r, 150v, 151v, 173v. As Thomson (2016) suggests, the surname 'Scaep' suggests that the scribe originated from the Low Countries.

decoNote.p: Large (2-8 lines) initials in red with decoration inside the letters; the major (8 lines) initial on f. 1r also features foliate pen-flourishing in brown ink; another one on f. 49v features a human faces drawn in red ink inside the letter.

note.p: A table of contents in a 16th- or 17th-century hand on i verso: Octo tract. MEdic. Magnini / Arnoldus de Villa nova de simpli. medic. / Jo: Mesue Canones vniu. / de simpl. med. et eiusem Antidotarius.

Quire letters in the lower right-hand corners of the first rectos and crosses in the lower right-hand corners on the second rectos of the inner most leaves of quires written in pencil by a 20th-century hand.

Miscellaneous: the number '170' has been written by a late medieval hand red ink at the top of f. 108v A possible reference or name has been inscribed by a late 15th- or early 16th-century hand at the top of f. 109r: 'f Class'.
There is loose plant material (a straw) in the gutter between ff. 106-107.

binding.p: Vellum binding over pasteboard: the vellum consists of a reused lease from Peterhouse, datable to c. 1700-1750, of which the reverse has been turned outwards. The binding contains a 17th- or 18th-century inscription in brown ink that runs from the rear cover to the front cover: The Master and fellows of Peterhouse - Mr Thomas ?Eale: [..] for 21 years / Michael [...]. The spine is inscribed with a title inscription in black ink: 'Tract. Med. de Mag. A. de Villa nova / Mesue'; and an old classmark number: '1-8-67' [with the '6' corrected to '7']; it also features a paper pastedown with the printed classmark number '182'. There is another (now illegible) inscription in brown ink on the book's lower edge.

provenance.p: Owned by Robert [? Barnlley], ? fl. 15th century [? Barnlley], Robert, ? fl. 15th century: their name inscribed on f. 122v: Roberd [Barnll]ey.

Owned by Thomas Deynman (fl. 1473, d. 1501), Bachelor of Medicine and Master of Peterhouse Deynman, Thomas, fl. 1473, d. 1501 , Bachelor of Medicine from an unidentified contintental university, physician to Henry VII and Lady Margaret Beaufort, fellow of Peterhouse from 21 April 1473, and Master from 19 November 1500 until his death in early 1501: his ownership inscriptions on f. i verso: Liber thome deynman medici' and ff. 108r and 173v: Constat Thome Deynman medico.

history.acquisition: Probably bequeathed to Peterhouse by Thomas Deynman (fl. 1473, d. 1501), Bachelor of Medicine and Master of Peterhouse Deynman, Thomas, fl. 1473, d. 1501 . The manuscript is perhaps one of the twenty of his 'better books' that one of the fellows was allowed to select. It was certainly at Peterhouse by 1589 since it is recorded as no. 22 in the shelf-list (now Peterhouse MS 400) of the Peterhouse library's contents compiled c. 1589-1592 and entitled 'Nomina librorum qui erant in Bibliotheca Collegii ante Doctorem Perne mortuum' (The names of the books that were in the library of the college before the death of Doctor Perne). Perne died in 1592. The book was recorded again, several years later, in the Ecloga Oxonio-Cantabrigiensis by Thomas James (1600), as no. 248. Peterhouse's book stamp features in the lower margins of ff. 1r, 77r, and 173v

Readers of this record are strongly encouraged to consult Thomson's Catalogue for further information. This catalogue entry also draws on M. R. availability.p: The majority of the western medieval manuscripts owned by Peterhouse, including MS 182, are on long-term deposit at Cambridge University Library. Entry to read in Cambridge University Library is permitted only on presentation of a valid reader's card. For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see Joining the Library). For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Manuscripts Reading Room.
